{"title_page": "Henry Charles Frank Morant", "text_new": "'''Henry Charles Frank Morant''' (1885{{spaced ndash}}28 October 1952) was an Australian writer and photographer. He was born at [[Dulverton]], [[England]] and died at [[St Kilda, Victoria]], [[Australia]].<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23211324 ''The Argus'', Melbourne, 29 October 1952.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\n''Whirlaway: a story of the ages'' was published in 1937. A young girl, Helen, and her pet [[koala]], Tirri, were taken on an adventure through the ages of time by Whirlaway, an elf-like creature. The book was illustrated by Florence Jean Elder. [[Race Mathews]] believed that ''Whirlaway'' never gained the recognition that it deserved because its publication in England in 1937 coincided with the lead-up to [[World War II]]. Few copies of the book reached Australia, and the London stocks were destroyed in [[The Blitz]]. Mathews considered that the book would have become an enduring favourite.<ref>[http://msfc.sf.org.au/proto-fan/ Melbourne Science Fiction Club.] Article by Race Mathews. Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\nMorant compiled an unpublished album of mounted photographs and documents on the Pioneers of Aviation. The manuscript is held by the [[National Library of Australia]].<ref>[http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Search/Home?lookfor=author:%22Morant,%20H.%20C.%20F%22 H. C. F Morant entry] at National Library of Australia. Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn December 1937 Morant was appointed publicity officer for the Ayrshire Cattle Herd Book Society of Australasia. He was the official photographer of some of the allied societies, and his photographs of livestock were acknowledged to be of a high standard.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article92477685 Chronicle (Adelaide, SA) 2 December 1937, Page 10.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref> He was official photographer for the Kennel Control Council.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11067828 The Argus 29 May 1937Page 32S.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* ''The Bibliography of Australian Literature K-O'', 2007, John Arnold and John Hay (editors), page 466.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141812290 The Australasian Saturday 4 December 1937, page 12.] Review of ''Whirlaway. Accessed 18 March 2015.''\n* ebook of [http://gutenberg.net.au/plusfifty-a-m.html#moranthcf ''Whirlaway''] by H F C Morant at [http://gutenberg.net.au Project Gutenberg Australia]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morant, Henry Charles Frank}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n", "text_old": "'''Henry Charles Frank Morant''' (1885{{spaced ndash}}28 October 1952) was an Australian writer and photographer. He was born at [[Dulverton]], [[England]] and died at [[St Kilda, Victoria]], [[Australia]].<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article23211324 ''The Argus'', Melbourne, 29 October 1952.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\n''Whirlaway: a story of the ages'' was published in 1937. A young girl, Helen, and her pet [[koala]], Tirri, were taken on an adventure through the ages of time by Whirlaway, an elf-like creature. The book was illustrated by Florence Jean Elder. [[Race Mathews]] believed that ''Whirlaway'' never gained the recognition that it deserved because its publication in England in 1937 coincided with the lead-up to [[World War II]]. Few copies of the book reached Australia, and the London stocks were destroyed in [[The Blitz]]. Mathews considered that the book would have become an enduring favourite.<ref>[http://msfc.sf.org.au/proto-fan/ Melbourne Science Fiction Club.] Article by Race Mathews. Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\nMorant compiled an unpublished album of mounted photographs and documents on the Pioneers of Aviation. The manuscript is held by the [[National Library of Australia]].<ref>[http://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Search/Home?lookfor=author:%22Morant,%20H.%20C.%20F%22 H. C. F Morant entry] at National Library of Australia. Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\nIn December 1937 Morant was appointed publicity officer for the Ayrshire Cattle Herd Book Society of Australasia. He was the official photographer of some of the allied societies, and his photographs of livestock were acknowledged to be of a high standard.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article92477685 Chronicle (Adelaide, SA) 2 December 1937, Page 10.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref> He was official photographer for the Kennel Control Council.<ref>[http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article11067828 The Argus 29 May 1937Page 32S.] Accessed 18 March 2015.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* ''The Bibliography of Australian Literature K-O'', 2007, John Arnold and John Hay (editors), page 466.\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Children's literature}}\n* [http://nla.gov.au/nla.news-article141812290 The Australasian Saturday 4 December 1937, page 12.] Review of ''Whirlaway. Accessed 18 March 2015.''\n* ebook of [http://gutenberg.net.au/plusfifty-a-m.html#moranthcf ''Whirlaway''] by H F C Morant at [http://gutenberg.net.au Project Gutenberg Australia]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Morant, Henry Charles Frank}}\n[[Category:1885 births]]\n[[Category:1952 deaths]]\n[[Category:Australian writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_Charles_Frank_Morant"}
{"title_page": "List of members of the 1st Parliament of Zimbabwe", "text_new": "This is a list of members of the [[1st Parliament of Zimbabwe]], which began in 1980 and expired in 1985. Per the [[Lancaster House Agreement]], 20 out of the 100 seats in the [[House of Assembly (Zimbabwe)|House of Assembly]] and 10 out of the 40 seats in the [[Senate of Zimbabwe|Senate]] were reserved for [[White people in Zimbabwe|white Zimbabweans]]. The 2nd Parliament's membership was set by the [[1980 Southern Rhodesian general election]], which gave [[ZANU\u2013PF]] a nearly 57 percent majority of common seats in the House of Assembly, with [[Zimbabwe African People's Union|PF\u2013ZAPU]] taking most of the remaining seats. The 20 seats reserved for whites were initially all held by the conservative [[Rhodesian Front]], but a majority later became independents.\n\n== Composition ==\n\n=== Senate ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"2\" |Party\n!Start\n!End\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{ZANU\u2013PF/meta/color}};\" |\n|[[ZANU\u2013PF]]\n|18\n|18\n|-\n| style=\"background:#DD0000;\" |\n|[[Zimbabwe African People's Union|ZAPU\u2013PF]]\n|2\n|2\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Rhodesian Front/meta/color}};\" |\n|[[Rhodesian Front|CAZ]]{{refn|The Rhodesian Front was succeeded in 1981 by the [[Republican Front (Zimbabwe)|Republican Front]], and in 1984 by the [[Conservative Alliance of Zimbabwe]].|group=note|name=\"caz\"}}\n|10\n|6\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Independent/meta/color}};\" |\n|{{Abbr|Ind.|Independent}}{{refn|Includes members of the [[Independent Zimbabwe Group]], a bloc formed by white independent MPs in 1983.|group=note|name=\"independent\"}}\n|0\n|4\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Independent/meta/color}};\" |\n|Chiefs\n|10\n|10\n|-\n| colspan=\"2\" |'''Total'''\n|'''40'''\n|'''40'''\n|}\n\n=== House of Assembly ===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Date\n! colspan=\"5\" |Party\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Total\n! rowspan=\"3\" |Vacant\n|-\n!\n!\n!\n!\n!\n|-\n![[Conservative Alliance of Zimbabwe|CAZ]]{{refn|The Rhodesian Front was succeeded in 1981 by the [[Republican Front (Zimbabwe)|Republican Front]], and in 1984 by the [[Conservative Alliance of Zimbabwe]].|group=note|name=\"caz\"}}\n![[United African National Council|UANC]]\n![[ZANU\u2013PF]]\n![[Zimbabwe African People's Union|ZAPU\u2013PF]]\n!{{Abbr|Ind.|Independent}}{{refn|Includes members of the [[Independent Zimbabwe Group]], a bloc formed by white independent MPs in 1983.|group=note|name=\"independent\"}}\n|-\n|14 May 1980 (opened)\n|20\n|3\n|57\n|20\n|0\n|100\n|0\n|-\n|October 1980\n|20\n|3\n|57\n|19\n|0\n|99\n|1\n|-\n|Late 1980<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3hVVAAAAYAAJ|title=Africa Research Bulletin|date=1980|publisher=Blackwell|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=5927|language=en}}</ref>\n|19\n|3\n|57\n|19\n|0\n|98\n|2\n|-\n|Early 1981<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QbkPAQAAMAAJ|title=Zimbabwe News|date=1998|publisher=Zimbabwe African National Union|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=11|language=en}}</ref>\n|19\n|3\n|57\n|20\n|0\n|99\n|1\n|-\n|January 1981<ref name=\":0\" />\n|20\n|3\n|57\n|20\n|0\n|100\n|0\n|-\n|April 1981<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&id=Tk5EAQAAIAAJ|title=Sub-Saharan Africa Report|date=1981|publisher=Foreign Broadcast Information Service.|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=135|language=en}}</ref>\n|19\n|3\n|57\n|20\n|0\n|99\n|1\n|-\n|June 1981<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7rwtx15jZaQC|title=Zimbabwe, a Country Study|date=1983|publisher=U.S. Department of the Army|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=214|language=en}}</ref>\n|18\n|3\n|57\n|20\n|0\n|98\n|2\n|-\n|July 1981<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Foisie|first=Jack|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=newGYsT1mtwC|title=Ian Smith Political Gains Aggravate Zimbabwe's Black-White Relations|d